[The epidemiology of influenza B viruses differs from that of influenza A
viruses -- influenza B viruses generally cause less severe outbreaks of
respiratory infection in man. However, the influenza B viruses are more
frequently implicated in the development of Reye's syndrome in children.
Reye's syndrome is rare, with only 0.37 to 0.88 cases per 100 000 children,
but it has been associated with 22 to 42 percent fatality. Influenza B
viruses were isolated first in 1940. However, there has been no indication
that hemagglutinin and/or neuraminidase subtypes comparable to those of the
influenza A viruses exist, although progressive antigenic variation can
generate different strains. The influenza B viruses appear to go through
cycles of prevalence. In some years influenza B viruses are virtually
absent, whereas in others they may predominate. In contrast to influenza A
viruses, which have natural reservoirs in pigs, horses, and birds, the
influenza B viruses are mainly isolated from humans. - Mod.CP]
